<P>
TROOPS FIGHT REBELS,ARREST SYMPATHIZERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and Wire reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Rwandan troops fought with guns and bombs for an eighth day to neutralize rebel 
invaders in the north of their tiny East African country, diplomats said. 
</P>
<P>
Western diplomats in Kigali, the capital, said they understand the Rwandan army 
is still meeting stiff opposition from the 2,000-strong rebel army, which 
stormed the country Sept. 30. In Kigali, government forces have arrested 
hundreds of suspected rebel sympathizers, officials said. The invaders, most of 
them from the Tutsi tribe, seek to oust the government, dominated by the rival 
Hutu tribe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
