<P>
THE SIDELINES; 
</P>
<P>
CHICAGO BEARS PICK WAUKEGAN PARK FOR WINTER TRAINING SITE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WAUKEGAN, Ill. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Chicago Bears have picked a Waukegan office and business park as the site 
of their cold-weather training facility. 
</P>
<P>
The Bears plan to lease the land at $1 a year and erect an inflatable temporary 
facility, said Patrick Fox, vice president and project manager of Amli 
Development, which owns the site. 
</P>
<P>
It will be 80 yards long, 60 yards wide and about 65 feet high, he said, with 
artificial turf and a constant temperature about 60 degrees. It should be 
available for use by Nov. 1. 
</P>
<P>
The deal is for two years, Fox said, with an option for a third. His long-term 
goal is to have the Bears build a permanent practice facility and headquarters 
at the site. 
</P>
<P>
The Bears accelerated their search for a cold-weather facility in August when 
players staged a protest during a rainy pre-season practice at Bear 
headquarters at Lake Forest. In the past, the team has suffered at Lake Forest 
with poor weather and frozen turf as the season wore on. 
</P>
</TEXT>
